title: Tired of Geyser servers always putting Java first? Check out the Realm of Aureus!
description: # Welcome to the Realm of Aureus! **NOTE: We are a *server*, NOT an actual realm!** Are you looking for a long-term adventure? A unique community you can call home, with no resets? Look no further! The Realm of Aureus combines the open-world survival and exploration aspect of vanilla Minecraft with the deep lore feel of an RPG. Our players are encouraged to build their bases, make friends, and strive to complete the most difficult tasks we have to offer. We can confidently boast over 500+ unique items, armors, enchantments, tools, skills, bosses, creatures and NPCs to explore and experiment with, all made in-house with an unmatched level of care and quality. The community drives our development priorities. We have a limitless well of ideas and content to release, but we will always prioritize community requests. # What we can offer: **Unique Bosses and Dungeons** - Fight bosses throughout the Realm! Use the terrain to your advantage, utilize boss weaknesses, and enjoy an exhilarating challenge as you fight through powerful foes to claim their hordes of loot! **World Border** - Explore out to a world border that expands by 1,000 blocks every Age. With an ever-expanding border, there is always fresh space to build on! **Java/Bedrock Parity** - Running on Geyser, we have done extensive testing and resource pack engineering to get all our textures and assets to be visually at one with both clients to the current capabilities of modern Minecraft. Share a cosmetic hat with your friends on both Bedrock and Java! **Territory Protection** - Protect your bases and builds from destruction with our easy to use land protection! Guard your territory, ally with other towns, and even form nations of smaller cities! **Achievement Hunting** - Complete over 400 special achievements with a varying range of difficulty from locating a rare piece of gear, to unlocking a unique chat title, or slaying a powerful boss - the more achievements you complete, the higher your fame progresses! **Leaderboards** - A fan favorite, there are leaderboards and stat trackers for all 400+ achievements in the game. Everything you achieve can be easily viewed in your achievement book! **Unique Cosmetics** - Wear a hat, a santa suit, or even a pair of colored wings! You name it, we have it. **Community Voting** - Vote in community polls to drive our content design. You can also post your own suggestions for people to vote on! **Experienced Staff Team** - Our staff team is small, passionate, and always willing to assist you. With nearly round-the-clock support, you can ensure that issues are met with the utmost urgency. **Non-P2W** - Most importantly, we offer only a single paid status, called Membership. This grants you access to all our bonus features and extra goodies and helps support our growing community costs in a sustainable and consumer friendly method. Version - **1.21.7 - 1.21.8** IP - **play.aureusmc.net** Bedrock Port - **19132** Discord - **https://discord.gg/rqsqNRK5U5(https://discord.gg/rqsqNRK5U5)** **What are you waiting for?!** *Come join our community today!*

title: What Are the Best Tools for Forecasting the Future?
description: From Crystal Balls to Data Models: The Smartest Ways We Peer Ahead Forecasting the future is both an art and a science. Whether youre a business strategist, a policy maker, or simply planning your personal goals, knowing how to peer around the corner gives you a powerful edge. In this post, we break down the best tools for forecasting the futurefrom traditional trend analysis to cutting-edge AI models. This guide will help you understand which forecasting tools are worth your time and how to use them effectively. (Main keyword: forecasting tools) Why Forecasting Matters More Than Ever Forecasting tools help individuals and organizations make better decisions in the face of uncertainty. With data flowing in from every direction and change happening at breakneck speed, reliable forecasting is no longer optionalits strategic. Whether youre predicting sales, assessing climate impacts, or planning urban growth, the right forecasting method can: Clarify potential futures Reduce risk and uncertainty Guide strategic choices Inform resource allocation In a volatile world, forecasting is your compass. The Top Forecasting Tools (and When to Use Them) Here are some of the most widely used and reliable tools for forecasting the future: 1. Trend Analysis Best for: Identifying historical patterns to project future outcomes Example Tools: Google Trends, market research reports When to Use: Early-stage planning, marketing, retail strategy Trend analysis is like reading tree ringsthe past leaves clues. By observing patterns in consumer behavior, product lifecycles, or economic shifts, we can extrapolate likely future outcomes. 2. Time Series Models (ARIMA, Exponential Smoothing) Best for: Quantitative forecasting based on historical numerical data Example Tools: R, Python (statsmodels), Excel When to Use: Forecasting revenue, demand, or inventory These models rely on historical data to detect seasonality, trends, and cyclic patterns. Think of them as statistical microscopes tuned to time. 3. Scenario Planning Best for: Exploring multiple possible futures based on key uncertainties Example Tools: Shell Scenario Planning Framework, Futures Wheel When to Use: Strategic planning, geopolitical risk, innovation forecasting Scenario planning doesnt predict the futureit prepares you for several plausible ones. Its especially useful when the future is shaped by unpredictable variables, like regulation or social change. 4. Predictive Analytics and Machine Learning Best for: Complex, high-volume data-driven forecasts Example Tools: TensorFlow, Prophet by Meta, AWS Forecast When to Use: Personalization engines, financial markets, predictive maintenance These AI-powered models can detect hidden patterns in vast data sets. Theyre great for systems where data volume or complexity overwhelms traditional methods. Real-World Example: Forecasting Retail Demand A global apparel company used time series models and Google Trends to predict demand across 40 markets. They layered in machine learning models to detect new patterns post-COVID. As a result, they reduced overstock by 30% and improved revenue predictability. This mix-and-match approach shows how combining tools gives better foresight. Summary: Choose the Right Tool for the Forecast Forecasting is not about having one magic toolits about selecting the right one for the job. Trend analysis, statistical models, scenario planning, and AI each have their place. Use them wisely, and youll move from guessing to guiding. Want more questions that sharpen your strategic thinking? Follow QuestionClasss Question-a-Day at questionclass.com. Bookmarked for You To dive deeper into forecasting and future thinking, here are three essential reads: The Art of the Long View by Peter Schwartz A classic on scenario planning from a Shell strategist. Superforecasting by Philip Tetlock and Dan Gardner A deep dive into what makes some forecasters consistently more accurate. Prediction Machines by Ajay Agrawal, Joshua Gans, and Avi Goldfarb Explores how AI is reshaping decision-making and forecasting. QuestionStrings to Practice QuestionStrings are deliberately ordered sequences of questions in which each answer fuels the next, creating a compounding ladder of insight that drives progressively deeper understanding. What to do now (understand your assumptions): Calibration String For aligning assumptions with data: What trend am I assuming here? How recent is that data? What would make that trend reverse? Try weaving this into forecasting discussions. Itll help you spot blind spots and build better models. Forecasting isnt about certainties its about building the clearest lens possible to see ahead. The better your tools, the sharper your vision.

title: mon parcours post etudes
description: En 2020 , après la pandémie du covid , je termine mon DUT informatique. J'oublie les dates de candidatures sur la plateforme E candidat. Je prend une annee sabbatique, je me met à parler à des oies. En 2021, je passe des entretiens et je finis par etre admis dans une licence PRO en data. La seule chose qu'on me demande en entretien est ce que tu sais faire du SQL et je dis que OUI. Voilà ou tout commence. Je trouve une alternance dans la fonction publique, je pensais à l'époque que l'importance c'est d'en avoir une que pas du tout et c'est tout. je suis data analyste qlik sense. Je continu en master, je trouve une alternance dans une ETI avec les outils pentaho data integrator et power bi , la fiche de poste c'était écrit data scientist notamment avec du python. En faite c'est plus développeur BI. J'apprends après mes études que ce qui compte ce sont les outils et le nom de l'entreprise qui compte pour avoir un JOB . Je fais des entretiens, on me propose : De faire du run avec un gars qui me claque des doigts quand je réfléchi et le but c'est juste donner des droits utilisateurs et faire de la documentation. On me propose un autre job avec un statut de technicien payé 1750 net pour faire de le data scientist sur des fichiers excel. Je dois sonner à un interphone pour rentrer dans les bureaux, j'ai pas de badge pour rentrer. Faire le tour des bureaux et ouvrir la porte du patron chaque matin et chaque soir. Signer une feuille comme quoi tu renonces à tes congés liés aux non fractionnements des congés. Depuis peu, on m'a proposé un job à 1450 net apres impot en CDD de 5 mois pour faire du support niveau 1.

title: First-year physics undergrad (GTÜ) wants a plasma physics projecthow do I pick a topic, what should I learn first, and where can I get help?
description: Hi all! Im a first-year physics student at **Gebze Technical University**. I want to start a **plasma physics** project (either experimental or simulation) and Im not sure how to choose a good, realistic topic for my level. **What Im aiming for** * Teaches me real plasma skills (diagnostics, basic modeling, or data analysis) * Safe + affordable (student budget), or purely computational **My background** * Math: Calc III, basic linear algebra/ODEs * Physics: intro mechanics + EM in progress * Coding: Python (NumPy/Matplotlib), a bit of MATLAB * Tools access: basic electronics bench at school I can probably get lab time if I find a supervisor **Constraints** * Budget is limited I can buy a few components or spend time learning open-source codes * I can commit 810 hrs/week this term Thanks a lot for any pointers! If you need more info about whats available at my department, I can ask around and share details.

title: Breaking into Quant
description: Whats up everyone. This might come off random but I am just thinking out loud at this point and wanted to hear from anyone in the quant world. I have a passion for technology and I recently have become very interested in Quant. I am 31 and I live in Cali. have no professional experience in quant for I have just started diving deep with theory and concepts. I have some experience with Python but in the grand scheme of things I know I am a novice. I want to make this a career for myself and make a change. I know I truly am late to the game but I am someone who has passion and truly will do anything I can to grow and learn everything I can to know the deep knowledge of quant. I want to mainly make my way into being a Quant Trader. I am currently doing self studies. Statistics, probability. Books. Hands on application with python and trying to get an idea of the space. My main reality is I know Im getting older, or old in the space of quant. But to be real, I am changing careers no matter what so this is what I want to do. I keep seeing degrees are an absolute must. I have only gone to college for 3 semesters and majored in Kinesiology so, completely different. Forgive me for babbling on but I want to know if its essentially too late. I know things arent always as black and white. Successful alphas. Being able to convey what I have learned and continuing to grow, I want to compete. My main ask is do you think I am able to break into the space at the age of 34 ish after I receive a bachelors. Or if a bachelors is truly needed to be with a larger firm or even a smaller firm. I know the filters, the doing self studies path and even while applying to jobs you are immediately rejected due to the lack of a degree for the hr filters. Could I learn and grow on my own and learn the ins and out of the trade and truly understand the math behind these decisions. Of course I am leaning towards self studies but I know this isnt like cybersecurity (which I have less than 6 months experience in) where you can get a cert and employers know you know the standard for security. But with quant its a different animal. Long story short, would the best route to get a bachelors in computer science and then continue or is it even possible for me to prove alpha and studies and knowledge to where I can start growing on my own and still get hired by providing proof of knowledge with projects and anything else that I need. Thanks for all your help in advance, I know its a lengthy entry. I appreciate all of you, thank you!

title: I built an AI with an AI - and it actually works. Here's how it went!
description: Tldr: I used Zo(https://www.zo.computer/) (using 4.5 sonnet as the LLM backend) to build an implementation of the LIDA(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LIDA_(cognitive_architecture)) cognitive architecture as an end-to-end stress test, and it was the first LLM tool I've seen deliver a complete and working implementation. Here's the repo to prove(https://github.com/mindpixel20/lida) it! Long version: A few days ago, I came across zo.computer(http://zo.computer/) and wanted to give it a try - what stood out to me was that it comes with a full-fledged linux VPS you've got total control over, in addition to workflows similar to Claude Pro. Naturally I wanted to use 4.5 Sonnet since it's always been my go-to for heavy coding work (there's a working FLOW-MATIC interpreter on my github I built with Claude btw). I like to run big coding projects to judge the quality of the tool and quickly find its limitations. Claude on its own, for instance, wasn't able to build up Ikon Flux(http://cadia.ru.is/wiki/_media/public:publications:ikonfluxrutrcs07006.pdf) (another cognitive architecture) - it kept getting stuck in abstract concepts like saliences/pregnance in IF context. I figured LIDA would've been a reasonable but still large codebase to tackle with Zo + 4.5 sonnet. The workflow itself was pretty interesting. After I got set up, I told Zo to research what LIDA was. Web search and browse tools were already built in, so it had no trouble getting up to speed. What I think worked best was prompting it to list out step by step what it'll need to do, and make a file with its "big picture" plan. After we got the plan down, I told it "Okay, start at step 1, begin full implementation" and off it went. It used the VM heavily to get a python environment up and running, organize the codebase's structure, and it even wrote out tests to verify each step was completed and functions as it should. Sometimes it'd struggle on code that didn't have an immediate fix but telling it to consider alternatives usually got it back on track. It'd also stop and have me run the development stage's code on the VM to see for myself that it was working, which was neat! So, for the next four or five-ish hours, this was the development loop. It felt much more collaborative than the other tools I've used so far, and honestly due to built-in file management AND a VM both me and Zo/Claude could use, it felt MUCH more productive. Less human error, more context for the LLM to work with, etc. Believe it or not, all of this was accomplished from a single Zo chat too. I honestly think Zo's capabilities set it apart from competitors - but that's just me. I'd love to hear your opinions about it, since it's still pretty new. But the fact I built an AI with an AI is freakin' huge either way!!

description: For Context, I'm a high school student, and was looking for either a free or affordable course(maybe on platforms like Udemy or any other), to learn C++, as I'm planning to give the INOI Olympiad (https://www.iarcs.org.in/inoi/(https://www.iarcs.org.in/inoi/)) ZIO(Zonal), so I can qualify for IOI(International Olympiad in Informatics). Any help is appreciated I particularly need resources from the community since most of the courses I see are focused on preping us for jobs, rather than olympiads

title: Why am I not getting interview calls after 700+ job applications in 3 months?
description: Hi everyone, Im a recent **Computer Science graduate(NIT)** and Ive been actively applying for jobs for the past **3 months**. Ive sent out more than **800+ applications** (for roles like **Software Engineer, SDE, Backend Developer**, etc.), but I havent received a **single interview call** not even a response from recruiters. Heres what Ive done so far: * Tailored my resume for each job * Added all my **projects** and **6-month internship experience** * Highlighted relevant skills (**C++, JavaScript, React, Node.js**, etc.) Despite all this, nothing seems to work and Im starting to feel stuck and demotivated. Id really appreciate any advice, feedback, or strategies that helped you land interviews as a fresher: * What changes should I make to my **resume**? * Are there better ways to **apply or network**? * Should I focus more on **open-source contributions**, new **projects**, or something else? Any honest feedback or tips would mean a lot.
